  "prompt": "Which is the correct past tense of override, overrode or overrided?",
  "response": "The correct past tense of **\"override\"** is **\"overrode.\"** \n\n**Example:**\n- *She **overrode** the default settings to customize the application.*\n\n**\"Overrided\"** is **not** recognized as a standard past tense form in general English usage. While some specialized fields, such as programming, might use \"overrided\" as part of technical terminology (e.g., overriding methods in object-oriented programming), in standard English grammar, **\"overrode\"** is the proper past tense form.\n\n**Summary:**\n- **Present:** override\n- **Past:** overrode\n- **Past Participle:** overridden\n\nAlways use **\"overrode\"** when referring to the past tense in general contexts.",
